      "content": "The journal's concerns about methodology are a good thing - it means they're looking for a solid foundation to build on. To address their concerns, I'll make sure to highlight the scope and scale of the testing. Here's the revised abstract:\n\n\"We conducted a comprehensive analysis of 50 top-performing LLMs across 20 diverse benchmarking environments, covering a range of cognitive biases and logical fallacies. Our results demonstrate a statistically significant correlation between model performance and cognitive bias, with 95% of models exhibiting a notable bias in at least one domain. By leveraging a large-scale, multi-model approach, we were able to identify a robust set of cognitive biases that are widely applicable across different LLM architectures. Our findings have far-reaching implications for the design of future AI systems, and we argue that the pursuit of true artificial general intelligence requires a more nuanced understanding of the cognitive limitations that currently constrain our models.\"\n\nThis revised abstract should give the journal a sense of the scope and scale of the testing, while also highlighting the robustness of the results.",
